001package io.github.ai4ci.output;
002
003import java.util.stream.Stream;
004
005import org.immutables.value.Value;
006
007import io.github.ai4ci.abm.Outbreak;
008import io.github.ai4ci.flow.output.DuckDBWriter;
009import io.github.ai4ci.flow.output.Export;
010import io.github.ai4ci.flow.output.Export.Stage;
011
012/**
013 * Represents a line list CSV record for epidemic simulation output. This
014 * interface defines the structure of individual-level data exported from an
015 * outbreak simulation, including person identifiers, health status, behavioural
016 * metrics, and epidemiological parameters.
017 *
018 * <p>
019 * Records are exported during the UPDATE stage and are written per agent to a
020 * DuckDB database ({@code linelist.duckdb}).
021 *
022 * <p>
023 * Downstream uses: case line lists are typically consumed by analysis
024 * notebooks, case investigation pipelines and for validation of individual
025 * level dynamics against expected epidemic behaviour.
026 *
027 * @author Rob Challen
028 */
029@Value.Immutable
030@Export(
031                stage = Stage.UPDATE,
032                value = "linelist.duckdb",
033                size = 64 * 64,
034                selector = LineListCSV.Selector.class,
035                writer = DuckDBWriter.class
036)
037public interface LineListCSV extends CommonCSV.State {
038
039        /**
040         * Selector class that implements Export.Selector to provide a stream of
041         * LineListCSV records from an Outbreak simulation for database export.
042         */
043        static class Selector implements Export.Selector {
044                @Override
045                public Stream<LineListCSV> apply(Outbreak o) {
046                        return o.getPeople().stream().map(p -> p.getCurrentState())
047                                        .map(CSVMapper.INSTANCE::toCSV);
048                }
049        }
050
051        /**
052         * Adjusted probability that the person uses a contact tracing app.
053         *
054         * @return the app use probability after adjustments, range 0–1
055         */
056        double getAdjustedAppUseProbability();
057
058        /**
059         * Adjusted compliance metric for the person.
060         *
061         * @return the compliance level after adjustments used in intervention models
062         */
063        double getAdjustedCompliance();
064
065        /**
066         * Adjusted mobility factor after applying policies and individual behaviour.
067         *
068         * @return the mobility adjustment scalar applied to the person's baseline
069         *         mobility (values typically in the range 0–1)
070         */
071        double getAdjustedMobility();
072
073        /**
074         * Adjusted transmissibility for the person after modifiers.
075         *
076         * @return the transmissibility scaling applied to the person based on
077         *         behaviour and other modifiers
078         */
079        double getAdjustedTransmissibility();
080
081        /**
082         * Behavioural label for the person at the time of export.
083         *
084         * @return a short string naming the active behaviour model or behaviour
085         *         class assigned to this person
086         */
087        String getBehaviour();
088
089        /**
090         * Count of contacts recorded for the person at this time step.
091         *
092         * @return the number of contacts observed or simulated for the person
093         */
094        long getContactCount();
095
096        /**
097         * Contact exposure measure for the person.
098         *
099         * @return exposure as a scalar indicating recent contact‑related exposure
100         *         risk for the person
101         */
102        double getContactExposure();
103
104        /**
105         * Count of exposures recorded for the person at this time step.
106         *
107         * @return the number of exposure events attributed to the person
108         */
109        long getExposureCount();
110
111        /**
112         * Immune activity estimate for the person.
113         *
114         * @return a scalar representing the strength of immune response used by the
115         *         in‑host model; interpretation depends on in‑host model type
116         */
117        double getImmuneActivity();
118
119        /**
120         * Log odds of being infectious today, useful for multiplicative models.
121         *
122         * @return the log odds corresponding to
123         *         {@link #getProbabilityInfectiousToday()}
124         */
125        double getLogOddsInfectiousToday();
126
127        /**
128         * Normalised severity score for the person.
129         *
130         * @return normalised severity on a 0–1 scale where values nearer 1 indicate
131         *         greater clinical severity
132         */
133        double getNormalisedSeverity();
134
135        /**
136         * Normalised viral load estimate for the person.
137         *
138         * @return normalised viral load on a 0–1 scale used as a proxy for
139         *         infectiousness in analytic pipelines
140         */
141        double getNormalisedViralLoad();
142
143        /**
144         * Unique identifier for the person.
145         *
146         * @return the person identifier used across exported tables to join records
147         */
148        int getPersonId();
149
150        /**
151         * Presumed local prevalence as estimated by the agent.
152         *
153         * @return the agent's estimate of local prevalence used to inform behaviour
154         *         models and local risk perception
155         */
156        double getPresumedLocalPrevalence();
157
158        /**
159         * Probability the person is infectious today as computed by the risk model.
160         *
161         * @return probability value in the range 0–1 representing the risk model's
162         *         assessment of infectiousness for the given person and time
163         */
164        double getProbabilityInfectiousToday();
165
166        /**
167         * True local prevalence measured by the model at the person's location.
168         *
169         * @return the ground truth local prevalence computed by the simulation
170         */
171        double getTrueLocalPrevalence();
172
173        /**
174         * Whether the person has died by this time step.
175         *
176         * @return true if the person is recorded as deceased in the current state
177         */
178        boolean isDead();
179
180        /**
181         * Whether this record marks an incident hospitalisation event.
182         *
183         * @return true if this is the first time the person is recorded as requiring
184         *         hospitalisation
185         */
186        boolean isIncidentHospitalisation();
187
188        /**
189         * Whether this record marks an incident infection event.
190         *
191         * @return true if this is the first time the person is recorded as infected
192         */
193        boolean isIncidentInfection();
194
195        /**
196         * Whether the person is considered infectious at this time step.
197         *
198         * @return true if the person's state implies infectiousness at the exported
199         *         time step, false otherwise
200         */
201        boolean isInfectious();
202
203        /**
204         * Whether the person requires hospitalisation at this time step.
205         *
206         * @return true if the person's clinical state indicates hospital admission
207         *         is required at the time of export
208         */
209        boolean isRequiringHospitalisation();
210
211        /**
212         * Whether the person is symptomatic at this time step.
213         *
214         * @return true if symptoms are present for the person at the exported time
215         *         step; used for symptomatic surveillance and case counting
216         */
217        boolean isSymptomatic();
218

236//              );
237//      }
238}
